          <td>{{Country}}</td>
          <td>{{Density}}</td>
        </tr>
      {{/pop_density}}
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <div><a class="details" href="#">show details</a>
    <div class="hidden">
      <p>
		    Papua New Guinea and its Melanesian neighbours count for 88% of the Pacific Island population (PNG =70%). These populations live on the biggest islands, and population density in the sub-region remains very low, except in cities. Micronesian and Polynesian countries have smaller populations, but their territories are archipelagos composed mainly of small islands, atolls and a few high islands. Density there is higher and reaches high values (higher than Japan or India), which are probably underestimated due to numerous uninhabited islands entering the calculation. These 2 sub-regions are also the most urbanized, and densities can reach locally, on some atolls, values comparable to those of Hong-Kong or Sydney. In many countries, population is concentrated on a few main islands and densities, which are higher there, will keep increasing with rapid population growth and rural emigration to urban places of these islands.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

